          "body": "1 Chronicles 13 opens with one of David's finest moments. He reads the Saul era correctly: the ark — the locus of God's throne on earth, the place of covenant meeting — had been neglected for forty years (13:3). The diagnosis is precise, the motive is pure, the consultation is broad (13:1-4). He names the failure by its right name: 'we did not seek Him' (*darash*, 13:3). The assembly endorses the proposal unanimously (13:4). Every indicator of a Spirit-blessed initiative is present. The problem is not motive but method. David does not ask *how* the ark is to be transported — only whether it should be. The distinction between the rightness of a goal and the rightness of a means is the chapter's central lesson, and it is written in the death of Uzza."
