          "title": "David's double response: anger and fear",
          "body": "Verses 11 and 12 record David's emotional arc with remarkable candor. First, anger: 'David became angry because of the LORD's outburst against Uzza' (13:11). The verb charah is the same word used for God's burning anger in 13:10 — the Chronicler's deliberate parallelism. David's anger is not condemned here, but it is also not endorsed. It is simply narrated as the initial human reaction to unexpected divine severity. Then, fear: 'David was afraid of God that day' (13:12). The anger converts to reverence — or at least to a terror that halts further action. Both responses are forms of taking God seriously, even if neither is fully adequate. The fear produces the right question ('How can I bring the ark of God home to me?', 13:12), which is the first seed of the corrective to come. Calvin notes that the fear of the Lord that begins in dread must mature into wisdom — and here we see David at the threshold of that journey."
